  <h2>the problem</h2>

  <p>skills only activate ~20% of the time. claude ignores them and answers from training data instead.</p>

  <div class="stats">
    <div>
      <div class="stat-value bad">20%</div>
      <div class="stat-label">baseline activation</div>
    </div>
    <div>
      <div class="stat-value good">84%</div>
      <div class="stat-label">with forced eval</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p>source: <a href="https://scottspence.com/posts/how-to-make-claude-code-skills-activate-reliably">scott spence's 200+ test study</a></p>

  <h2>what we learned</h2>

  <h3>skill triggering is pure llm reasoning</h3>

  <p>no algorithmic routing. no regex. no embeddings. claude reads skill descriptions and decides. the description is the only signal.</p>

  <h3>what makes skills activate</h3>

  <table>
    <tr>
      <th>pattern</th>
      <th>why it works</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><code>Use when:</code> clause</td>
      <td>explicit trigger conditions</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>specific terms</td>
      <td>"axum, tonic, sqlx" not "backend"</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>action verbs</td>
      <td>"building", "debugging", "configuring"</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>front-loaded keywords</td>
      <td>claude matches against description start</td>
    </tr>
  </table>

  <h3>the fix</h3>

  <p>force claude to evaluate each skill before responding:</p>

<pre><code>Before responding, you MUST:

1. EVALUATE each skill in &lt;available_skills&gt;:
   - State: [skill-name] - YES/NO - [reason]

2. ACTIVATE relevant skills:
   - For each YES, call Skill(name) BEFORE proceeding

3. Only THEN respond.</code></pre>

  <p>this simple system prompt takes activation from 20% to 84%+.</p>

